\begin_layout Section
Calibrating the Fabry Perot
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us start with the assuming that you have a bright fringe at the centre.
 Let the distance initially between the two mirrors of the etalon be 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 So in this situation we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2d_{1}=n\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is some arbitrary number, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is wavelength of prashansa.
 Now suppose you move one of the mirrors such that the new distance is 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{2}=d_{1}+\Delta d'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta d'$
\end_inset

 is what you measure using the screw guage.
 Also, let us assume that the centre is bright again, and a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 fringes collapsed to the centre in the process of changing the distance.
 Then, ideally we must have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\Delta d'=m\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know all the quantities in the equation.
 However, in practice, there'll be some error, which can be removed by calibrati
on.
 Thus we define the expected distance by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta d\equiv m\lambda/2
\]

\end_inset

And we define our calibration constant
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\frac{\Delta d}{\Delta d'}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Determining the Space Between the Mirrors of the Etalon
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis for this part rests on the assumption that effect displayed
 in the following figure can be neglected.
 We'll show later by simple calculations the range of the radius for which
 this can be neglected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start simple.
 From trigonometric arguments, we have the following relation between the
 angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{m}$
\end_inset

 of a ray from the source to the screen
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
with respect to the line joining the centre of the pattern and the source
\end_layout

\end_inset

, corresponding to a bright fringe, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is a number (which will be defined soon), and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{m}$
\end_inset

, the radius of the ring on the screen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{r_{m}}{D}=\tan\theta_{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For small angles, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tan\theta_{m}=\theta_{m}=\frac{r_{m}}{D}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we look at the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th large bright ring from the aforesaid ring.
 For this also, we correspondingly have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tan\theta_{m+n}=\theta_{m+n}=\frac{r_{m+n}}{D}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now give meaning to number 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 For the first ring, the condition for being bright is given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2d\cos\theta_{m}=m\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the wavelength of the incident laser light.
 Then it follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2d\cos\theta_{m+n}=(m-n)\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the minus sign is owing to the fact that we've assumed the 
\emph on
larger 
\emph default
ring to correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{m+n}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{m+n}>\theta_{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We eliminate 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 from these equations to obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2d(\cos\theta_{m+n}-\cos\theta_{m})=-n\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use small angle approximation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta=1-\theta^{2}/2$
\end_inset

, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d(\theta_{m+n}^{2}-\theta_{m}^{2})=n\lambda
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which in terms of observables, is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{r_{m+n}^{2}-r_{m}^{2}}{D^{2}}=\frac{n\lambda}{d}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So finally we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d=\frac{n\lambda D^{2}}{r_{m+n}^{2}-r_{m}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Small Angle Approximation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have assumed that the analysis given above works, so long as the distance
 
\begin_inset Formula $2d\tan\theta<1mm$
\end_inset

, the least count of the radius measurement apparatus.
 We then find the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 for which this is valid and thereby determine the radius of fringes we
 can use, without the theory failing.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $d\approx2cm$
\end_inset

 in our setup, so we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta<0.025$
\end_inset

, and using 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\approx\tan\theta=d/D$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $D=70$
\end_inset

cm, thus the radius must have the following contraints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
