r<1.75cm
\]

\end_inset

for confident results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The setup has very curious similarities with the michelson interferometer.
 First note that in the michelson interferometer, there are three cases
 to be considered
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Point source (the black paper with hole dosn't function as a very good point
 source)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Non coherent extended source (the diffuser case)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first case, we would obtain a pattern on a screen, but won't be able
 to see it.
 In the second case we won't see it on a screen.
 However we (experimentally known) can see it directly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One could verify these results in the Fabry Perot setup as well.
 With a point source (the diode laser, with or without an additional lense),
 when viewed through the fabry perot, doesn't yield a pattern, although
 you get it on a screen.
 Conversely, if you converted the point source into an extended source,
 the pattern on the screen dissapears, however you can now observe it directly
 through the etalon.
 In complete agreement with the predictions.
\end_layout

